DIV1.P:
In acknowledgment of the great Assistance he receiv'd from this Service, he writes to the Queen a long Letter, throughout which he expresses his Grateful Sense of it; but in particular, as it respects the whole Kingdom, as well as the Queen, he has, among others, this high Expression;
I receive so great an Assistance from your Majesty and your GENEROUS NATION, that I am overcome with your Goodness, and in the greatest Confusion, that I should be the Oc∣casion of so great an Expence for the Supporting my Interest. And after other lofty Expressions, his Majesty concludes thus;
I am ever, with the most sincere Affection, Respect and Gratitude, Madam, My Sister, Your most Affectionate Brother, CHARLES. From the Camp at Senia before Bar∣celona, Octob. 22. 1705.
